<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>I think the /consider command could use some changes. What do you think?</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois.cgi?Eli">Eli</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 4:43 p.m. 26/7/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> I think the /consider command could use some changes. What do you think?<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/images/datel.gif" width=46 height=22 border=0><img src="http://www.everworld.net/images/dateblnk.gif" width=100 height=22 border=0><img src="http://www.everworld.net/images/dater.gif" width=306 height=22 border=0></center><BR></STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#F4D99F FACE=arial>
<P>Hi all,

<P>I am an avid Everquest player (more like an addict) and I think I may have
<BR>found something that would make the game better for role-playing.
<P>As you all know, on occasion the only way to resolve an issue it to duel it
<BR>out. However, I see a major problem with the way /consider affects dueling
<BR>(and role-playing). It is true that in order to role-play there are many
<BR>cases where you need to size-up a possible opponent in order to respond
<BR>correctly. Yet I have never known anyone who can always tell exactly how
<BR>dangerous an opponent is in reality or other RPGs as well as the /consider
<BR>can. Personally, I try to be as ambiguous about my level as possible when
<BR>playing. None the less, anyone who is close to me in level can easily
<BR>determine my level plus or minus one to three levels simply by conning me.
<BR>For you non-role-playing people, this is even more problematic. Why would
<BR>you duel someone when you can determine the outcome before the duel even
<BR>starts? You mite as well /consider your opponent, if it is an even match
<BR>duel it out, otherwise declare the stronger victor and save your self the
<BR>time.
<P>So here is my idea. MAKE A CONSIDER SKILL that you could use to size-up an
<BR>opponent then the skill could fail giving you a false impression of how
<BR>strong an opponent is and you could improve it like other skills. This would
<BR>be more realistic. Then make /con useful only to determine if you can group
<BR>or not. This revised /con would not tell you if the PC you are conning is
<BR>stronger or weaker but just that you may group with them.
<P>Well, what do you all think, Good, Bad or Otherwise?
<P>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
